tx-swr32: Dark Flaring Analysis
================================

Identifies unpermitted ("dark") flaring in the Permian Basin by
cross-referencing three public datasets:

  1. SWR 32 exception permits — scraped from the Texas RRC
  2. RRC well locations — parsed from EBCDIC bulk data files
  3. VIIRS Nightfire — satellite-detected flares from EOG/NOAA

The pipeline spatially matches satellite flare detections to nearby
wells, then checks whether those wells had valid SWR 32 flaring
permits at the time of detection.

Current results: 87 flare sites with 6,021 detection-days across
2012-2026, none covered by an SWR 32 exception permit.


Setup
-----
Requires: uv, duckdb CLI, Playwright (chromium)
Optional: EOG account for VNF data (credentials in .env)

  uv sync
  uv run playwright install chromium
  make db


Next steps: well-to-operator linkage
-------------------------------------
All operator_name values in the output are currently NULL. The
operator lookup goes: well -> lease number -> permit -> operator_no
-> operators table. This fails because the wells matched by VNF
mostly don't appear in the SWR 32 permits (that's the point — they're
unpermitted).

To get operators for dark flare sites, the wellbore EBCDIC file has
an operator number field that we're not currently extracting. It
lives in the type 01 root record (the exact byte offset needs
investigation — likely bytes 16-21 or similar). Extracting it in
parse_rrc.py and adding an operator_no column to wells.csv would
let the analysis join directly:

  wells.operator_no -> operators.operator_number -> operator_name

This would answer "who is flaring without a permit?" rather than
just "where is unpermitted flaring happening?"
